---
import ReportLayout from "../../../layouts/ReportLayout.astro";
import Section from "../../../components/Section.astro";
import { chapterHref, chapterNavItems } from "../../../lib/chapters";
import { chrome, localePath } from "../../../lib/i18n";

const locale = "en" as const;
const nav = chapterNavItems(locale);
const t = chrome(locale);
const selfHref = localePath(locale, "guides/computer-use");
const ch01 = chapterHref("01-log-is-the-runtime", locale);
const ch02 = chapterHref("02-evidence-before-compression", locale);
---

<ReportLayout
  title="Computer Use six contracts · Agent Atelier"
  description="Maka Desktop Computer Use: observation authority, bind/validate, cua-driver ownership, evidence classes, and host events — a companion report, not a seventh worldview chapter."
  nav={nav}
  activeHref={selfHref}
  locale={locale}
>
  <article class="report">
    <header class="masthead">
      <p class="masthead__eyebrow">Companion guide · Specimen: maka-agent · {t.doneLabel}</p>
      <h1>
        <span class="masthead__title-zh">Computer Use six contracts</span>
        <span class="masthead__title-en">Computer-use contract suite</span>
      </h1>
      <p class="masthead__sub">
        Stacked Desktop foundation contracts: observation-frame authority, action binding, sole native
        executor, evidence qualification. Orthogonal to the §01–§06 worldview — enter from
        <a href={`${ch01}#mcp`}>§01 · MCP</a> / <a href={`${ch01}#permission`}>#permission</a>, then
        read here.
      </p>
      <div class="masthead__meta">
        <span>Home · /guides/computer-use</span>
        <span>Research · #47</span>
        <span>
          <a href={localePath("zh", "guides/computer-use")}>中文</a>
        </span>
      </div>
    </header>

    <Section
      id="scene"
      label="CU · Scene"
      title="Why contracts — not a demo reel"
      lede="Coordinates, focus, occlusion, and process generation turn “click once” into TOCTOU."
    >
      <p>
        Computer Use turns model intent into real window input. Allowing “re-pick the current topmost
        window,” auto-replay on unknown outcomes, or treating approval as observation freshness yields
        irreversible side effects on the wrong target. Maka pins the boundary with six current
        contracts plus <code>packages/computer-use</code> and Runtime
        <code>openai-computer-*</code> tests; when docs disagree, <strong>code + contract tests
        win</strong>.
      </p>
      <blockquote class="pull">
        Observation owns coordinates; cua-driver owns dispatch; approval never proves freshness.
      </blockquote>
    </Section>

    <Section
      id="six"
      label="CU · Six docs"
      title="How the six contracts stack"
      lede="Foundation is the non-breakable floor; other layers pin model path, evidence qualification, host events, and artifact integrity."
    >
      <ol class="plain-list numbered">
        <li>
          <code>computer-use-foundation-contract.md</code> — observation / binding / validation /
          execution ownership / postcondition / service lifecycle / approval+privacy / presentation
          isolation.
        </li>
        <li>
          <code>computer-use-model-loop-foundation.md</code> — primary <code>maka_computer</code>;
          native OpenAI <code>computer_call</code> observation-only by default.
        </li>
        <li><code>computer-use-evidence-classes.md</code> — four evidence classes.</li>
        <li><code>computer-use-provider-evidence.md</code> — provider matrix and sanitizer.</li>
        <li><code>computer-use-host-events-contract.md</code> — typed attributable producers + gaps.</li>
        <li><code>cua-driver-artifact-integrity.md</code> — pin/hash; not notarization.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        Headless is out of foundation scope. CLI is experimental opt-in only. Coordinate / pixel /
        CGEvent paths are described as disabled and fail closed.
      </p>
    </Section>

    <Section
      id="observation"
      label="CU · Observation"
      title="Observation authority and action binding"
      lede="Coordinates are meaningful only inside the producing frame; mutations claim before the first async boundary."
    >
      <ul class="plain-list">
        <li>
          Each executable observation: unique <code>frameId + epoch</code>, screenshot size,
          <code>pid + windowId</code>, capture-local coordinates; Electron page identity when
          applicable.
        </li>
        <li>Dispatch <strong>must not</strong> re-select the current global topmost window.</li>
        <li>
          New observation, turn/session end, abort, user stop, service loss, and explicit intervention
          invalidate old action claims and keyboard ownership.
        </li>
        <li>
          Mutations snapshot, normalize, fingerprint, and claim before the first async boundary, bound
          to the active observation; ordered actions serialize per Computer Use session.
        </li>
        <li>
          Stale / replay / unclaimed / malformed / targetless → fail closed; no bare-pixel or focus-steal
          fallback.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <h3 class="subhead">Exact target validation</h3>
      <p>
        Coordinate actions verify the same window identity, geometry, screenshot scale, page identity,
        and occlusion. Semantic actions prefer stable-token refetch; otherwise only a unique
        identity-preserving match. Irrelevant AX/DOM churn must not synthesize
        <code>user_intervened</code>.
      </p>
    </Section>

    <Section
      id="executor"
      label="CU · Executor"
      title="cua-driver is the sole native executor"
      lede="The agent must not move the real mouse, steal foreground, or perform windowless desktop input."
    >
      <p>
        Window/page discovery, semantic preparation, input dispatch, and effect readback stay inside
        the cua-driver boundary. Keyboard ownership binds
        <code>session + turn + generation + pid + windowId + page/frame</code> and is revoked on
        failure, stale, new observation, intervention, service-generation change, and turn/session end.
        Child process exit with unknown action outcome → <strong>re-observe</strong>; never auto-replay.
      </p>
      <h3 class="subhead">Postcondition</h3>
      <ul class="plain-list">
        <li>After a successful mutation, the old observation is consumed and a fresh full observation returns.</li>
        <li>Transport success ≠ business success; <code>verified:true</code> needs action-specific effect/readback.</li>
        <li><code>supported:true, ok:false</code> is a terminal failure for that action.</li>
        <li>Retries use a fresh observation and a new claim — never old coordinates/fingerprints.</li>
      </ul>
    </Section>

    <Section
      id="approval"
      label="CU · Approval"
      title="Graded leases: approval ≠ freshness"
      lede="PermissionEngine and CU leases are both gates — do not collapse them into “approved.”"
    >
      <p>
        Approval is an app capability gate (graded short leases for metadata / screenshot / pointer /
        keyboard / semantic mutation), not proof of active observation or action freshness. Re-authorize
        when target, action class, observation, or session generation changes. Sensitive apps,
        secure/password fields, and unsupported destinations fail closed. Screenshots, typed text,
        coordinates, raw AX, window titles, secrets, and raw page content stay out of durable session
        logs / telemetry / evaluation reports by default.
      </p>
      <p>
        Presentation (cursor/PiP) sits <strong>downstream</strong> of targeting: it cannot select,
        transform, authorize, or rewrite execution coordinates. <code>readyForInteraction</code> may
        only affect timing via bounded fail-open; <code>finished</code> does not block native dispatch.
        See <a href={`${ch01}#permission`}>§01 · PermissionEngine</a> for park/grant control flow — a
        different door.
      </p>
      <aside class="history-aside" id="cursor-contrast">
        <p class="history-aside__tag">History contrast · Codex FogCursor</p>
        <p>
          Maka’s virtual cursor is a <strong>visual interaction layer</strong>, not a click backend —
          a successful press still precedes the ordinary synthetic / native event path. Recovered from
          the Codex Computer Use binary: glyph path, hotspot = hosting-view center, and
          MotionConfiguration constants. The candidate-path scorer is stripped, so Maka uses a
          deterministic 20-candidate cubic planner — a <strong>structural reproduction</strong>, not
          instruction-for-instruction equivalence. Not a Runtime protocol seam; a presentation-boundary
          contrast. Specimen: <code>docs/codex-cursor-reverse-engineering.md</code>.
        </p>
      </aside>
    </Section>

    <Section
      id="model-loop"
      label="CU · Model loop"
      title="Primary path maka_computer; native computer is observation-only by default"
      lede="AX / semantic first; validate a whole native batch before any action executes."
    >
      <pre class="code-block" aria-label="Model path">model function/tool call
  → Computer Use facade
  → observed AX element identity
  → stale-element refetch + uniqueness
  → element executor (AXPick / AXPress / AXValue…)
  → synthetic event fallback only inside native executor</pre>
      <p>
        Provider adapters must not infer a missing observation ID or silently bind to “the current
        frame.” Under OpenAI strict schemas the adapter projects action-allowed keys; the core
        <code>maka_computer</code> parser stays provider-neutral and strict. Real provider evidence
        lives in the provider-evidence contract; without credentials use hermetic-protocol — never
        upgrade it to real-runtime.
      </p>
    </Section>

    <Section
      id="evidence"
      label="CU · Evidence"
      title="Four evidence classes are qualification boundaries"
      lede="Missing evidence is invalid/inconclusive — never inferred from fixture state alone."
    >
      <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Evidence classes" tabindex="0">
        <table class="proto-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th scope="col">Class</th>
              <th scope="col">Meaning</th>
              <th scope="col">Fills a real matrix cell?</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><code>real-runtime</code></td>
              <td>Live provider + production Runtime + owned fixture + cua-driver</td>
              <td>Yes (when the report contract is met)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>fault-injection</code></td>
              <td>Named failure injected (e.g. wrapper intervention)</td>
              <td>No — useful regression, cannot qualify</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>hermetic-protocol</code></td>
              <td>Local protocol server; no live-credential claim</td>
              <td>No</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>static-contract</code></td>
              <td>Source/schema/deterministic harness</td>
              <td>No</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>
        Distinct from <a href={ch02}>§02</a> tool-result evidence vocabulary: here the topic is
        <strong>provider qualification</strong>. The sanitizer keeps action types/timing/result codes and
        strips coordinates, typed text, raw UI, credentials, and provider payloads.
      </p>
    </Section>

    <Section
      id="host-events"
      label="CU · Host events"
      title="Connect only typed, attributable events"
      lede="AX/DOM content churn ≠ physical intervention."
    >
      <ul class="plain-list">
        <li>
          Typed outcomes: <code>user_intervened</code> → re-observe; <code>screen_locked</code> →
          locked; <code>blocked_url</code> → terminal; unknown/unavailable/mismatch → re-observe.
        </li>
        <li>
          cua-driver service release clears executor-local observations / keyboard ownership and advances
          the Runtime session.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Physical-input guard (host-owned)</strong>: Desktop wires
          <code>powerMonitor.getSystemIdleTime() &lt; 1</code> as a conservative ~1s quiet window
          (whole-second granularity). The backend invokes <code>physicalInputRecentlyActive</code> at
          the last practical boundary before every mouse / keyboard / semantic / scroll / drag / text
          dispatch; if input is active or idle state cannot be read → <code>user_intervened</code>,
          <strong>no</strong> cua-driver input tool call, consumed observation invalidated, explicit
          re-observe required.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Compatibility CGEvent off by default</strong>: PID-bound compatibility delivery can
          interleave with physical button state, so production keeps
          <code>allowCompatibilityInputDispatch !== true</code> — coordinate click / scroll / drag /
          <code>press_key</code> / semantic→pixel fallback blocked. Retained: observation, screenshots,
          wait, zoom, virtual cursor, native AX, <code>set_value</code>, uniquely targeted Electron CDP
          semantic / <code>insertText</code>. Controlled tests may opt in explicitly.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Deliberate gaps</strong>: a quiet window is <strong>not</strong> a global
          physical-input producer claim; raw error-string matching is not an accepted producer; Codex’s
          signed turn-ended helper is not invoked. Re-enabling coordinate input needs a native executor
          that proves its event backend does not perturb global physical button state.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </Section>

    <Section
      id="backend-selection"
      label="CU · Backend selection"
      title="selectComputerUseBackend: honest none without a pinned binary"
      lede="The packages/computer-use entry is not “always cua-driver” — platform and artifact preconditions decide backendId."
    >
      <p>
        Specimen: <code>packages/computer-use/src/select-backend.ts</code>. Non-
        <code>darwin</code>, missing <code>binaryPath</code> +
        <code>expectedBinarySha256</code>, or backend construction throw →
        <code>backendId: 'none'</code>: no disposable backend; tools expose empty
        <code>sessionEvents</code> (all <code>unobserved</code>). Desktop must inject the pinned
        artifact path + hash; missing pin ≠ silent fallback to compatibility CGEvent.
      </p>
      <ul class="plain-list">
        <li>
          Success path: <code>createCuaDriverBackend</code> →
          <code>buildComputerUseTools(&#123; backend, overlay? &#125;)</code> →
          <code>backendId: 'cua-driver'</code>.
        </li>
        <li>
          <code>onSessionInvalidated</code> wires <code>tools.sessionEvents.reobserveRequired</code> —
          service loss must force re-observe, not silently retarget windows.
        </li>
        <li>
          <code>hostBundleId</code> defaults to <code>com.maka.desktop</code> (overridable via
          <code>MAKA_CU_HOST_BUNDLE_ID</code> / explicit option).
        </li>
      </ul>
    </Section>

    <Section
      id="cua-driver-lifecycle"
      label="CU · cua-driver lifecycle"
      title="Dual roles, generation, restart budget"
      lede="Action and capture are two long-lived children; exit under unknown outcome → re-observe, never auto-replay."
    >
      <p>
        Specimen: <code>cua-driver-service.ts</code> · <code>cua-driver-release.ts</code> ·
        <code>cua-driver-result.ts</code>. Each <code>CuaDriverService</code> owns one
        <code>role</code> (action / capture), JSON-RPC transport, a <code>generation</code> counter,
        and <code>restartAttempts</code> (default max 3, 50ms backoff). Handshake / request timeouts
        and stdout buffer caps are pinned; wrong identity (binary hash / server name / version /
        protocol) is rejected at handshake.
      </p>
      <ul class="plain-list">
        <li>
          Spawn uses <code>--no-overlay</code>: the native executor does <strong>not</strong> paint UI;
          presentation is a downstream overlay hook.
        </li>
        <li>
          Release / dispose clears executor-local observations and keyboard ownership and advances the
          Runtime session generation — every prior claim dies.
        </li>
        <li>
          <code>normalizeCuaDriverOutcome</code>: forbids dressing foreground / compatibility dispatch
          as a foundation success path; unknown child outcome → typed re-observe, not a retry of the
          old fingerprint.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </Section>

    <Section
      id="snapshot-coordinates"
      label="CU · Snapshot coordinates"
      title="Logical screen point ↔ same-frame screenshot pixels"
      lede="Coordinate authority lives inside the snapshot frame that produced it; malformed transforms fail closed."
    >
      <p>
        Specimen: <code>cua-driver-snapshot.ts</code> · <code>display-snapshot.ts</code>.
        <code>resolveWindowAtDeclaredPoint</code> scales the declared point with
        <code>desktopFrameWidthPx / logicalDisplayWidth</code>, then picks a z-order hit inside window
        bounds; non-finite positive width/height → undefined (reject). Multi-display uses
        <code>resolveCuaDisplaySnapshots</code> — never smuggle one display’s logical coordinates onto
        another’s pixels.
      </p>
      <p>
        Read with foundation “Observation owns coordinates”: a model-declared point is dispatchable
        only under the same <code>frameId + epoch</code> and matching geometry / scale / page identity.
      </p>
    </Section>

    <Section
      id="presentation-overlay"
      label="CU · Presentation overlay"
      title="createComputerUseOverlayHook: downstream cursor, not click backend"
      lede="readyForInteraction may affect timing only; finished never blocks native dispatch."
    >
      <p>
        Specimen: <code>computer-use-overlay-hook.ts</code>. The hook projects coordinate actions onto
        an <code>OverlayCursorSink</code> (move / complete / cancel); actions without coordinates get a
        resolved fence (immediately ready/finished). Presentation <strong>cannot</strong> choose
        windows, rewrite execution coordinates, or act as approval. Contrast
        <a href="#approval">#approval</a> / <a href="#cursor-contrast">#cursor-contrast</a>: the
        virtual cursor is a visual layer.
      </p>
    </Section>

    <Section
      id="artifact"
      label="CU · Artifact"
      title="Integrity check ≠ distribution-ready"
      lede="check:cua-driver-artifact pins local/pre-package inputs; distributionReady stays false."
    >
      <p>
        The repo pins one macOS universal cua-driver: archive/binary SHA-256, version, arm64+x86_64,
        structural code signature, license/source-claim hashes. It does <strong>not</strong> prove
        reproducible builds, trusted attestation, full SBOM, or Developer ID nested signing /
        notarization / Gatekeeper. Integrity checks are intentionally outside
        <code>check:release</code> until the release pipeline supplies provenance.
      </p>
    </Section>

    <Section
      id="evidence-hardening"
      label="CU · Evidence hardening"
      title="How real-model reports fail closed as evidence"
      lede="Harvest durable policy from archive hardening; do not relitigate PR diaries."
    >
      <p>
        Unified report boundary: every direct or Desktop report passes one schema-driven sanitizer.
        Only validated attribution, terminal state, action summaries, synthetic fixture state,
        assertion results, and allowlisted dispatch evidence survive. Prompts, screenshots,
        coordinates, typed text, raw UI, arbitrary traces, provider bodies, and outer exception
        messages are stripped.
      </p>
      <ul class="plain-list">
        <li>
          A real provider matrix cell requires: schema v1 + <code>real-runtime</code> evidence;
          matching provider / model / scenario / producer / live transport; launcher
          <code>pass</code> with terminal <code>complete/end_turn</code>; successful allowed actions
          bound to the owned fixture; per-action count budgets plus expected/forbidden-effect
          assertions; AX or semantic dispatch evidence for mutation scenarios.
        </li>
        <li><strong>Missing evidence is invalid or inconclusive — never a pass.</strong></li>
        <li>
          Delivery honesty (archive <code>computer-use-delivery-state.md</code>): delivered but
          unverifiable writes/semantic actions return <code>outcome_unknown</code> — do not mislabel
          readback/screenshot failure as <code>capture_failed</code> and erase “may have taken
          effect.” Observations enter the bounded FIFO only after screenshot normalization succeeds.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </Section>

    <Section
      id="failures"
      label="CU · Failures"
      title="Fail-closed matrix (teaching)"
      lede="Stop rather than guess the target."
    >
      <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Failure matrix" tabindex="0">
        <table class="proto-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th scope="col">Situation</th>
              <th scope="col">Result</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Claim on an old frame</td>
              <td>stale → fail closed</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Missing / ambiguous semantic target</td>
              <td>Reject; no guessing</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Occlusion / geometry / scale / page change</td>
              <td>Reject</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Model omits <code>observation_id</code></td>
              <td>Typed tool error; must re-observe</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Transport OK but effect fails</td>
              <td><code>supported:true, ok:false</code></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Unknown child outcome</td>
              <td>re-observe; no auto-replay</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Delivered but readback/screenshot unverifiable</td>
              <td><code>outcome_unknown</code> (keep delivered; not <code>capture_failed</code>)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Fault-injected intervention</td>
              <td>Regression OK; cannot fill a real cell</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Physical input active / idle unreadable (pre-dispatch guard)</td>
              <td>
                <code>user_intervened</code>; no cua-driver input call; observation invalidated →
                re-observe
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Compatibility CGEvent path (production default)</td>
              <td>
                <code>unsupported_action</code> / blocked — not “quiet window allows”
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Quiet window alone claimed as safe coordinate input</td>
              <td>
                <strong>Teaching error</strong> — can still perturb physical button state (archive
                physical-input-guard)
              </td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <aside class="history-aside">
        <p class="history-aside__tag">Verification</p>
        <p>
          <code>packages/computer-use/src/__tests__/*</code> ·
          <code>packages/runtime/src/__tests__/openai-computer-*.test.ts</code> · Desktop
          <code>computer-use-host.test.ts</code> / <code>computer-use-capability.test.ts</code> (idle-time
          wiring) · operator commands <code>e2e:computer-use-real</code> / <code>process-restart</code> /
          <code>real-model</code>. Archive hardening +
          <code>computer-use-physical-input-guard.md</code> contribute durable policy only — not PR
          archaeology. Outline: <code>docs/research/computer-use-six-contracts-deep-outline.md</code>.
        </p>
      </aside>
    </Section>
  </article>
</ReportLayout>

